The employee attends all required meetings and briefings, able to answer inquiries on any unit being tracked in the process. Aware of units that are behind schedule, what problems are being worked and the status of the resolution. The employee must be able to accomplish all duties and tasks associated with the MOB/DEMOB mission assigned by the 1JMB Operations Officer. Develops and maintains logs, rosters, status boards, charts, graphs, and presentations, schedules and coordinates deployment and redeployment activities for units mobilizing. Tracks operational movement and provides situation updates, Tracks flight schedules from mobilization stations. title: Access Control Point Supervisor
description: Acts as Installation Courtesy Ambassador for base populous and general public. Prepares reports of activities completed by the Visitor Center Team. Resolves problems with completing tasks that are identified by the Visitor Center Specialist (such as resolving issues with conflicting directives or guidelines). Trains or arranges for training of team members to accomplish work tasks. Ensures customers use the materials and equipment provided to facilitate their visit. Coordinates work schedules with employees and the Visitor Center Manager. Ensures complete coverage of work areas during tour of duty. Checks and verifies, within the limits of government provided date, identification media (Military or DOD ID Card), state driver’s license, or other form of state or federal government-issued photo ID card. Ensures identification media has not been altered or otherwise tampered with. Authorizes access to the installation. Verifies that individuals have a valid need to enter the installation. When required, verifies destination of individual requesting access. Interprets data provided, input elements into relational databases, and provide synthesized data to supervisors for input to master reports. Assists military, federal and local law enforcement agencies during VIP visits and other post-wide events. Evaluates and makes recommendations on matter of safety and security. Assess on-the-sport situations to identify suspicious activities/personnel/materials. Report persons suspected of suspicious activity such, but not limited to attempting to unlawfully enter the installation or presenting false identification documentation.

title: SIGINT Operations & Analysis Center Officer-In-Charge
description: I directed the signals intelligence operations and activities of over 30 personnel. This included providing oversight and guidance of two teams of analysts. Further, I provided operational guidance and direction over two subordinate units, composed of 20 Marines each, in the conduct of full-spectrum signals intelligence operations. During this period of time I led and directed the team’s efforts to answer the critical intelligence requirements of the Commanding General, II Marine Expeditionary Force (Forward) that further served in contributing to the intelligence needs of theater and national customers. Previous to this deployment, as the 2d Radio Battalion Training Officer, I planned and executed mission critical training requirements for over 400 Marines in order to ensure enhanced skill sets were developed amongst the organization.
